On July 14, 2026, Anthropic launched [Claude for Teachers](https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-for-teachers), giving verified K-12 educators in the US free access to premium Claude capabilities, a library of teaching skills, and evidence-based curricula mapped to academic standards in all 50 states.

If you teach, or you build the tools that teachers use, this launch matters. It ships a classroom-ready version of Claude, but it also opens up new connectors, an open-source skills repository, and a technical write-up for anyone building in education. Here's what shipped, how it works, and where developers fit in.

# What is Claude for Teachers?

**Claude for Teachers is a free offering for verified US K-12 educators that pairs premium Claude capabilities with a curated set of teaching skills and access to evidence-based, standards-aligned curricula.** It's built for the day-to-day work of teaching, including planning lessons, differentiating materials, and making sense of class data, without the planning spilling into every evening.

Once an educator is verified, they get access to Claude with the Learning Commons connector and a set of tailored teaching skills grounded in learning science. The offering also includes Claude Code and Claude Cowork, so Claude can carry longer tasks forward on its own rather than stopping at a single reply.

# Why Anthropic built Claude for Teachers

Decades of research show that practices like differentiation, mastery-based learning, and small group instruction reliably improve student achievement. The problem is rarely knowing what works. It's finding the time and resources to do it. Budgets are tight, classes are often too large to meet every student individually, and planning eats into evenings. That strain falls hardest on under-resourced schools.

Anthropic frames Claude for Teachers as a way to close the gap between educational best practice and what a teacher's week actually allows. The framing is backed by an important nuance in the early evidence: while the impact of AI tools *for students* is mixed and depends heavily on implementation, AI tools *for teachers* can strengthen instructional practice and improve student outcomes. Claude for Teachers is aimed squarely at the teacher's craft, so educators can protect what they value most, which is time with their students.

# What Claude for Teachers connects to

Anthropic connects Claude to academic standards and established curricular resources to help teachers create more relevant, standards-aligned materials.

At the center is **Learning Commons**, which gives Claude access to academic standards across all 50 states, and beneath each standard, the smaller learning competencies it's built from and the order students typically learn them. So when Claude drafts a lesson, the plan is scaffolded and aligned to teaching standards rather than generic. On top of that, Claude for Teachers brings in trusted curricular resources like [OpenSciEd](https://www.openscied.org/) and IM v.360 from [Illustrative Mathematics](https://www.illustrativemathematics.org/).

Educators can also connect Claude across an entire ecosystem of K-12 tools:

* **ASSISTments** generates auto-scored, standards-aligned math problems for practice and assessment.
* **Brisk Teaching** turns ideas into interactive student activities and standards-aligned lessons in seconds.
* **Canva Education** turns lesson materials into classroom-ready designs and interactive experiences.
* **Coteach** creates high-quality math diagrams grounded in K-12 curriculum.
* **Diffit** creates and adapts instructional materials for every student.
* **Eedi** generates diagnostic questions that reveal student thinking, in English and Spanish.
* **MagicSchool** makes instructional content classroom-ready.
* **Snorkl** surfaces insights about classes, assignments, and student progress to inform instruction.
* **TeachFX** gives personalized instructional feedback grounded in real classroom talk.

# How does Claude for Teachers work?

**After verification, a K-12 educator gets Claude with the Learning Commons connector and a set of teaching skills co-developed with Learning Commons and grounded in learning science.** Those skills were designed around the tasks teachers said mattered most, evaluated for rigor and classroom usability, and refined with feedback from real classrooms, including schools like Prospect Schools in Brooklyn.

Two skills anchor the experience.

**Plan a lesson from high-quality instructional materials.** Ask for a lesson and Claude draws on widely used curricula mapped to your state's standards, plus the fine-grained learning components and progressions beneath them. It drafts a plan and student-facing materials you can revise and take straight into class.

**Differentiate for every learner in your room.** Ask Claude to adapt materials for students at different readiness levels, and it builds a differentiation plan plus personalized student-facing materials for each proficiency level. Scaffolds make the material accessible, while students who are ready get further challenge.

Because Claude for Teachers includes Claude Code and Cowork, it can also run longer, multi-step work:

* **Analyze class data to plan instruction.** Hand Claude a folder of data, such as a roster, diagnostics, attendance, and your own notes, and it builds a clear picture of where every student is, so you can tailor instruction. You control what's shared, and nothing you share is used in model training.
* **Schedule repeated tasks.** Hand off a task once, like reviewing each day's exit tickets and adapting tomorrow's plan to match, and it runs every school day at 4pm. Claude works while you drive home.

# How does Claude for Teachers handle student data?

Anthropic says Claude for Teachers is educator-only, includes terms designed for K-12 privacy, and protects student information through a K-12 Data Processing Addendum written to comply with FERPA. Anthropic also says data submitted through Claude for Teachers is not used for model training.

The offering follows Claude's 18-and-over policy, so it's for teachers rather than students. Anthropic is also working with the [American Federation of Teachers](https://www.aft.org/) to align its terms and privacy practices with a developing "Gold Standard" for the sector.

> "We've been working with Anthropic on a Gold Standard that sets out industry best practices for safety and privacy in K-12 education," said Randi Weingarten, President of the American Federation of Teachers. "It's important that Anthropic is committing to these principles in their new Claude for Teachers, a tool designed by and for educators to assist them instructionally and hopefully give them more time for the human relationships at the heart of learning."

# AI fluency training for teachers

Alongside the product, Anthropic released **AI Fluency for K-12 Teachers**, a course co-created with [Teach for America](https://www.teachforamerica.org/), plus a train-the-trainer module co-created with the American Federation of Teachers. The guidance is model-agnostic, Creative Commons-licensed, and practical, covering which classroom tasks AI is suited for and how to use it responsibly with students. Because it's model-agnostic and openly licensed, it's useful even to educators and schools not using Claude.

# Public goods for the education community, and where builders come in

This is the part that should interest developers. As part of Anthropic's Beneficial Deployments mission, Claude for Teachers ships with a set of open resources for anyone building in education:

* **New connectors** published in Anthropic's directory.
* **An open-source repository** of the teaching skills.
* **A technical write-up** of how the skills were evaluated, so other builders can apply the same approach.

Anthropic is also piloting an evaluation of Claude for Teachers in the **Detroit Public Schools Community District** to study impact on educator wellbeing and practice, and the work ties into its partnership with the [Gates Foundation](https://www.gatesfoundation.org/) to co-develop tools that improve K-12 outcomes. On top of that, **Playlab** will support a national network of lab schools, helping educators become *builders* of the AI tools used in their classrooms.

That last point is particularly relevant for developers. It points toward a growing ecosystem of connectors, skills, and purpose-built tools created by educators and EdTech teams. Many of those tools will need authentication, data storage, file handling, and server-side workflows.

# How to get started with Claude for Teachers

**Once verified, US K-12 educators get Claude for Teachers entirely free.** Sign up by **June 30, 2027** for a full year of access. Claude for Teachers is for individual educators today, and a dedicated offering for schools and districts is coming soon. In the meantime, districts interested in Claude can use Claude for Nonprofits.

# What this means if you build education tools on Appwrite

If you're building an education connector, a classroom app, or a Claude-powered agent, the model is only half the stack. Agents and apps still need authentication, stored state, file persistence, and server-side logic between steps. Wiring that up by hand is exactly what slows teams down on the path from prototype to product. Education tools may handle sensitive information, making secure authentication and careful data management especially important. Teams should independently assess their institution's privacy, security, data residency, retention, and regulatory requirements before deploying any backend.

That's where [Appwrite](/) fits. Appwrite gives your app a production backend out of the box: [Auth](/auth) for teacher and admin accounts, [Databases](/databases) for rosters and progress data, [Storage](/storage) for lesson materials and student uploads, and [Functions](/functions) for the server-side logic your agent triggers between steps.

If you want a Claude-powered agent to stand up that backend without manually assembling infrastructure, the **Appwrite plugin for Claude Code** bundles the Appwrite API MCP server, the Appwrite Docs MCP server, and SDK-specific agent skills into a single install. With the appropriate project access and permissions, Claude Code can interact with Appwrite APIs and documentation while helping developers implement services such as Auth, Databases, Storage, Sites, and Functions. It's the same pattern we covered when [Claude Fable 5 returned with stronger jailbreak safeguards](/blog/post/claude-fable-5-returns-with-stronger-jailbreak-safeguards).

So if you're building for teachers rather than teaching yourself, you can [start for free on Appwrite Cloud](https://cloud.appwrite.io/), explore the [integrations directory](https://appwrite.io/integrations), or join the conversation on the [Appwrite Discord](https://appwrite.io/discord). Claude can help you build the classroom experience, while Appwrite provides the backend services needed to move it toward production.

